WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.090 --> 00:00:04.480
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: So it's my great pleasure
to introduce one of the deepest and most prolific

00:00:04.480 --> 00:00:05.480
economists.

00:00:05.480 --> 00:00:06.950
Joe Stiglitz.

00:00:06.950 --> 00:00:14.100
Joe is a superb academic who has extensively
applied his expertise in the political sphere.

00:00:14.100 --> 00:00:17.280
As well as in the journals.

00:00:17.280 --> 00:00:21.080
Joe is famous for studies of the affects of
asymmetric information.

00:00:21.080 --> 00:00:23.660
For which he won the Nobel Prize in 2001.

00:00:23.660 --> 00:00:30.710
He's one of the earliest to apply game theoretic
reasoning for studying policy issues.

00:00:30.710 --> 00:00:37.350
His work revolutionized the study of credit
markets, insurance, development, and the theory

00:00:37.350 --> 00:00:43.329
of the firm, where he is responsible for the
concept of efficiency wages.

00:00:43.329 --> 00:00:45.210
You should all like efficiency wages.

00:00:45.210 --> 00:00:48.660
That's what gets us paid more than the competition.

00:00:48.660 --> 00:00:52.850
He served in the Clinton Administration as
the Chair of the President's Council on Economic

00:00:52.850 --> 00:00:53.850
Advisers.

00:00:53.850 --> 00:00:58.780
He also served as Chief Economist of the World
Bank where he's noted for criticizing the

00:00:58.780 --> 00:00:59.789
World Bank.

00:00:59.789 --> 00:01:00.789
[laughter]

00:01:00.789 --> 00:01:08.789
He's a co-author of the inter-governmental
panel on climate change.

00:01:08.789 --> 00:01:14.119
More recently he's, Joe Stiglitz has been
advising Obama but has also been sharply critical

00:01:14.119 --> 00:01:21.279
of the Obama Administration's financial industry
rescue plan.

00:01:21.279 --> 00:01:26.090
To give a quote, he said "Whoever designed
the bank rescue plan is either in the pocket

00:01:26.090 --> 00:01:27.469
of the banks, or incompetent."

00:01:27.469 --> 00:01:28.469
[laughter]

00:01:28.469 --> 00:01:31.170
And I hope he will tell us which.

00:01:31.170 --> 00:01:32.170
[laughter]

00:01:32.170 --> 00:01:39.849
Without further ado, let me introduce one
of the best economists, Joe Stiglitz.

00:01:39.849 --> 00:01:42.609
[extended applause]

00:01:42.609 --> 00:01:50.780
&gt;&gt;Joe: Well, it's a real pleasure to be here
again.

00:01:50.780 --> 00:01:58.929
The subject of course, that I'm talking about
is not so, uh, attractive.

00:01:58.929 --> 00:02:01.619
The topic is "The price of inequality.

00:02:01.619 --> 00:02:04.919
How today's divided society endangers our
future."

00:02:04.919 --> 00:02:10.950
The book grew out of an article that I wrote
in Vanity Fair.

00:02:10.950 --> 00:02:16.719
Vanity Fair is maybe not the usual media for
academics to publish in.

00:02:16.719 --> 00:02:24.480
But the Vanity Fair article did get more attention
than my 1969 Econometrica article on the same

00:02:24.480 --> 00:02:25.480
subject.

00:02:25.480 --> 00:02:26.480
[laughter]

00:02:26.480 --> 00:02:32.489
The title of the Vanity Fair article went
viral.

00:02:32.489 --> 00:02:38.709
Was "Of the One Percent, By the One Percent,
For the One Percent."

00:02:38.709 --> 00:02:43.420
And you can sort of get the tone of the article.

00:02:43.420 --> 00:02:52.660
And it got picked up by a part of the chant
of the Occupy Wall Street.

00:02:52.660 --> 00:02:57.680
The issues that I'm talking about are not
the politics of envy as one of the political

00:02:57.680 --> 00:02:59.340
candidates has said.

00:02:59.340 --> 00:03:02.749
One of the political candidates has said "You
shouldn't be talking about inequality except

00:03:02.749 --> 00:03:05.790
to quiet rooms in hushed tones."

00:03:05.790 --> 00:03:11.540
But in fact, I believe that inequality is
one of the most important problems our society

00:03:11.540 --> 00:03:12.980
faces today.

00:03:12.980 --> 00:03:18.370
And needs to be talked about actually quite
loudly.

00:03:18.370 --> 00:03:27.430
What most Americans do not realize is that
quietly without people noticing it, America

00:03:27.430 --> 00:03:34.170
has become the advanced industrial country
with the highest level of inequality.

00:03:34.170 --> 00:03:38.969
And we were already at, had that distinction
a number of years ago.

00:03:38.969 --> 00:03:44.569
But while other countries have worked hard
to contain the inequality, to slow the increase.

00:03:44.569 --> 00:03:52.629
In recent years the level of inequality in
the United States has been increasing markedly.

00:03:52.629 --> 00:04:00.420
Just a couple examples, the share of income
that accrues to the upper one percent has

00:04:00.420 --> 00:04:07.599
doubled from 10 percent in 1980 to 20 percent
today.

00:04:07.599 --> 00:04:15.620
The, there are a number of other statistics
that describe the degree of inequality.

00:04:15.620 --> 00:04:22.660
Perhaps one, two, I think that maybe I should
mention in the beginning here.

00:04:22.660 --> 00:04:26.760
One of them is that Americans like to think
of our country as a land of opportunity.

00:04:26.760 --> 00:04:30.590
It really defines part of the American identity.

00:04:30.590 --> 00:04:39.340
But in fact, that notion that America is a
land of opportunity is really a myth.

00:04:39.340 --> 00:04:43.680
Now we all know people who've made it from
the bottom to the top, middle to the top.

00:04:43.680 --> 00:04:48.090
Immigrants who come to the United States and
succeeded.

00:04:48.090 --> 00:04:52.820
But from the point of view of the economist,
what's relevant is the statistics.

00:04:52.820 --> 00:04:58.270
Not the examples, not the exceptions, but
what happens on average.

00:04:58.270 --> 00:05:07.139
And on average, America is less equal even
than old Europe, let alone any of the other

00:05:07.139 --> 00:05:09.460
advanced industrial counties for which there's
data.

00:05:09.460 --> 00:05:10.460
What does that mean?

00:05:10.460 --> 00:05:19.960
It means that the life prospects of a young
kid in the United States is more dependent

00:05:19.960 --> 00:05:25.710
on the education and income of his parents
than in any other country.

00:05:25.710 --> 00:05:30.259
And you can see, it gets reflected in a number
of aspects.

00:05:30.259 --> 00:05:35.340
Both in terms of movement, up, but also movement
down.

00:05:35.340 --> 00:05:43.449
People at the top who don't do very, whose
children don't do very well in school, wind

00:05:43.449 --> 00:05:48.460
up with higher income than people from the
bottom and middle whose children do very well

00:05:48.460 --> 00:05:49.580
in school.

00:05:49.580 --> 00:05:57.460
So it really shows the influence of parents
in determining opportunity in the United States.

00:05:57.460 --> 00:06:08.560
Some of you may have seen the article that
appeared yesterday reflecting the outcome

00:06:08.560 --> 00:06:15.580
results of the Fed's survey of wealth and
income in the United States.

00:06:15.580 --> 00:06:17.790
The most recent one.

00:06:17.790 --> 00:06:19.670
And it was very, very telling.

00:06:19.670 --> 00:06:26.580
You know, it would be one thing if all that
success at the top benefited everybody.

00:06:26.580 --> 00:06:30.280
And the idea that that was so is called 'trickle
down' economics.

00:06:30.280 --> 00:06:35.710
You know, you throw enough money at the top,
and everybody benefits.

00:06:35.710 --> 00:06:38.970
The evidence is to the contrary.

00:06:38.970 --> 00:06:46.181
That while the top has done very well, the
median, people 50 percent below, 50 percent

00:06:46.181 --> 00:06:47.539
above.

00:06:47.539 --> 00:06:54.849
Median income in the United States today is
lower than it was a decade and a half ago.

00:06:54.849 --> 00:06:59.940
And what's been happening to wealth is even
more troubling.

00:06:59.940 --> 00:07:05.919
The top one percent controls about 40 percent
of all the wealth.

00:07:05.919 --> 00:07:11.389
But the recession was really, really bad for
most Americans in terms, not only in terms

00:07:11.389 --> 00:07:16.270
of income, but even more so in terms of wealth.

00:07:16.270 --> 00:07:18.069
Not a surprise.

00:07:18.069 --> 00:07:25.470
But with people at the bottom and middle putting
all their wealth into the homes, when the

00:07:25.470 --> 00:07:31.870
home prices went down, on average over 30
percent, in some areas over 50 percent, they

00:07:31.870 --> 00:07:38.020
lost a very large fraction of their wealth.

00:07:38.020 --> 00:07:44.949
So in fact, the wealth, particularly of the
middle, and the bottom, is now back to where

00:07:44.949 --> 00:07:47.270
it was over two decades ago.

00:07:47.270 --> 00:07:52.169
No increase in wealth over two decades.

00:07:52.169 --> 00:08:02.400
The, in the recovery from the crisis in 2010,
we got another picture of the degree of inequality

00:08:02.400 --> 00:08:03.919
in our society.

00:08:03.919 --> 00:08:11.110
93 percent of the growth that occurred in
2010 went to the upper one percent.

00:08:11.110 --> 00:08:22.420
So again, most Americans are not sharing in
what's going on.

00:08:22.420 --> 00:08:33.340
It would be one thing, as I said, if the success
of those at the top income benefited everybody.

00:08:33.340 --> 00:08:34.340
But it hasn't.

00:08:34.340 --> 00:08:41.020
And also it would be one thing if the successes
at the top reflected their contribution to

00:08:41.020 --> 00:08:42.100
society.

00:08:42.100 --> 00:08:43.960
This is not about envy.

00:08:43.960 --> 00:08:48.690
The question is, have they really made contributions
that are commensurate with their incomes?

00:08:48.690 --> 00:08:53.760
And those of you who study elementary economics
know this is a 19th century theory called

00:08:53.760 --> 00:08:55.900
the 'marginal productivity theory.'

00:08:55.900 --> 00:09:01.500
Well, the crisis actually gave lie to that
theory.

00:09:01.500 --> 00:09:12.190
We all saw in the crisis the bankers walking
off with huge bonuses even though they brought

00:09:12.190 --> 00:09:14.630
to the global economy to the brink of ruin.

00:09:14.630 --> 00:09:17.410
Even though they brought their own company
to the brink of ruin.

00:09:17.410 --> 00:09:23.820
In fact, some of the banks were so embarrassed
about calling these bonuses "performance bonuses"

00:09:23.820 --> 00:09:27.480
that they changed the name to "retention bonuses".

00:09:27.480 --> 00:09:30.940
There was no "performance" so they had to
have another name.

00:09:30.940 --> 00:09:35.970
But then the question was "Why would you wanna
retain somebody who had messed up your company

00:09:35.970 --> 00:09:42.070
so badly?" and all this actually speaks to
one of the key issues that I raise in the

00:09:42.070 --> 00:09:43.070
book.

00:09:43.070 --> 00:09:45.280
What is the true source of wealth?

00:09:45.280 --> 00:09:48.230
Of those say, at the top?

00:09:48.230 --> 00:09:53.880
If you look at the list of people at the top,
it doesn't include the great innovators.

00:09:53.880 --> 00:09:58.150
You know the people who invented the computer,
Turing.

00:09:58.150 --> 00:10:03.040
It doesn't include the people who invented
the transistor.

00:10:03.040 --> 00:10:04.040
The laser.

00:10:04.040 --> 00:10:05.040
That discovered DNA.

00:10:05.040 --> 00:10:09.100
None of these people who really made important
contributions to our society are in that list

00:10:09.100 --> 00:10:14.260
of the wealthiest in our society.

00:10:14.260 --> 00:10:20.260
It's basically with the argument I have is,
a very large proportion of these are people

00:10:20.260 --> 00:10:22.230
that economists call "rent seekers."

00:10:22.230 --> 00:10:25.530
Let me try to explain what the concept of
rent-seeking is.

00:10:25.530 --> 00:10:26.980
You can see it in a couple ways.

00:10:26.980 --> 00:10:29.330
There are two ways to create wealth.

00:10:29.330 --> 00:10:30.650
To get wealth.

00:10:30.650 --> 00:10:34.140
One of them is to make the size of the national
pie larger.

00:10:34.140 --> 00:10:36.450
And to get a share of that increase.

00:10:36.450 --> 00:10:42.080
The other one is to try to seize a larger
share of the existing pie.

00:10:42.080 --> 00:10:44.590
And that's what rent seekers do.

00:10:44.590 --> 00:10:49.710
And in that process they actually make the
pie smaller.

00:10:49.710 --> 00:10:52.500
So an example are monopolists.

00:10:52.500 --> 00:10:54.650
How do monopolists make their profits?

00:10:54.650 --> 00:10:56.270
Partly by restricting output.

00:10:56.270 --> 00:11:00.180
They're making the output actually smaller
than it otherwise would be.

00:11:00.180 --> 00:11:07.730
And yet that can generate large, large incomes
for themselves.

00:11:07.730 --> 00:11:15.480
So if you look at the disproportionate people
at the top, they are in this group of what

00:11:15.480 --> 00:11:17.190
economists will call rent seekers.

00:11:17.190 --> 00:11:21.910
Let me give you a couple other examples.

00:11:21.910 --> 00:11:27.520
When the bankers engage in predatory lending,
or abusive credit card practices, what they're

00:11:27.520 --> 00:11:29.000
doing is moving money.

00:11:29.000 --> 00:11:30.250
They're not creating value.

00:11:30.250 --> 00:11:35.350
What they're doing is taking money from poor
Americans, financially unsophisticated Americans

00:11:35.350 --> 00:11:38.300
and moving it from the bottom to the top.

00:11:38.300 --> 00:11:39.550
That doesn't create wealth.

00:11:39.550 --> 00:11:41.640
It actually in some sense destroys wealth.

00:11:41.640 --> 00:11:43.930
Why does it destroy wealth?

00:11:43.930 --> 00:11:51.350
Well, one of the most important resources
of any society are their human talent.

00:11:51.350 --> 00:11:53.270
The young people.

00:11:53.270 --> 00:12:00.410
And when you devote those people to this task
of moving money from the poor people.

00:12:00.410 --> 00:12:02.600
Through predatory lending.

00:12:02.600 --> 00:12:07.360
You misallocating your scarcest human resource.

00:12:07.360 --> 00:12:13.160
So it's not a surprise, and this is really
one of the most important points of the book.

00:12:13.160 --> 00:12:20.670
It's not a surprise that economies in which
the divide is larger, when the inequality

00:12:20.670 --> 00:12:22.960
is larger, grow more slowly.

00:12:22.960 --> 00:12:29.220
You see that in the history of the United
States and the period in the decades after

00:12:29.220 --> 00:12:31.180
World War II.

00:12:31.180 --> 00:12:33.170
We had just fought a war together.

00:12:33.170 --> 00:12:37.080
And there was a sense of national cohesiveness.

00:12:37.080 --> 00:12:42.780
We passed laws like the GI Bill, that provided
education for all.

00:12:42.780 --> 00:12:48.160
The result of that was our economy went through
the most rapid period of economic growth and

00:12:48.160 --> 00:12:52.720
it was a period in which every part of our
economy grew.

00:12:52.720 --> 00:12:54.550
Those at the bottom grew most rapidly.

00:12:54.550 --> 00:12:58.480
So that the divide between the top and the
bottom got reduced.

00:12:58.480 --> 00:13:05.170
Since 1980 what has happened is growth has
slowed.

00:13:05.170 --> 00:13:07.820
And the divide has grown.

00:13:07.820 --> 00:13:09.110
And that's not an accident.

00:13:09.110 --> 00:13:13.880
And one of the things I try to do in the book
is to try to explain why there is this negative

00:13:13.880 --> 00:13:17.550
correlation between inequality and growth.

00:13:17.550 --> 00:13:21.220
Why inequality is bad for economic growth.

00:13:21.220 --> 00:13:25.240
And there are a couple factors that help explain
it.

00:13:25.240 --> 00:13:29.850
One of them is, this phenomena of rent-seeking
that I just described.

00:13:29.850 --> 00:13:36.820
That resources got misallocated to seeking
rents, rather than to producing increasing

00:13:36.820 --> 00:13:37.820
value.

00:13:37.820 --> 00:13:41.120
And there are a whole list of the kinds of
rent-seeking activities.

00:13:41.120 --> 00:13:48.510
When the drug companies spend money to persuade
congress to give them a drug, to pass a law

00:13:48.510 --> 00:13:53.870
that says "The us government, while it's the
largest purchaser of drugs, cannot bargain

00:13:53.870 --> 00:13:59.720
with the drug companies, the result of which
gives the drug companies a gift over 10 years

00:13:59.720 --> 00:14:02.370
of a half a trillion dollars.

00:14:02.370 --> 00:14:05.930
Money that could go into making our economy
more productive.

00:14:05.930 --> 00:14:12.220
That's rent-seeking activity that does not
lead to a stronger economy.

00:14:12.220 --> 00:14:19.080
When we have a tax law again, as a result
of lobbying, that says that speculators should

00:14:19.080 --> 00:14:26.790
be taxed at less than half a rate, the rate
that those who work for a living.

00:14:26.790 --> 00:14:30.940
Because the special provisions capital gains,
we're destroying our economy.

00:14:30.940 --> 00:14:32.810
More resources move into speculation.

00:14:32.810 --> 00:14:34.310
Less into creative activity.

00:14:34.310 --> 00:14:38.500
And again, our economy is weaker.

00:14:38.500 --> 00:14:40.280
It's also of course, not fair.

00:14:40.280 --> 00:14:46.680
And it's one of the reasons that the top one
percent pays an average tax rate of 15 percent.

00:14:46.680 --> 00:14:52.620
Which is much less than those whose income
is substantially lower.

00:14:52.620 --> 00:14:58.170
There are other reasons that inequality is
bad for our economy.

00:14:58.170 --> 00:15:05.490
For an economy to work well, there needs to
be a basic level of public spending on basic,

00:15:05.490 --> 00:15:08.790
on what you might call the common good.

00:15:08.790 --> 00:15:14.010
You have to have investments in education,
public education.

00:15:14.010 --> 00:15:18.750
One of the reasons why we've become a less
equal society is that we are not investing

00:15:18.750 --> 00:15:21.530
as much in public education.

00:15:21.530 --> 00:15:26.940
People in California know that access to the
university is becoming much less restricted.

00:15:26.940 --> 00:15:30.780
And it's not as open as it was 30 years ago.

00:15:30.780 --> 00:15:35.610
And these are things that mean that many young
people are not gonna live up to their potential.

00:15:35.610 --> 00:15:37.740
And again a waste of resources.

00:15:37.740 --> 00:15:41.700
You need to invest in technology.

00:15:41.700 --> 00:15:43.860
Google.

00:15:43.860 --> 00:15:54.050
A lot of the most important innovations of
the recent decades are based on government

00:15:54.050 --> 00:15:55.540
funded research.

00:15:55.540 --> 00:15:58.820
The internet was supported by government funded
research.

00:15:58.820 --> 00:16:05.720
We've been living off, draining the well,
of ideas that basic research helped support.

00:16:05.720 --> 00:16:08.110
But we haven't been refilling the well.

00:16:08.110 --> 00:16:10.550
And that requires government support.

00:16:10.550 --> 00:16:11.700
National Science Foundation.

00:16:11.700 --> 00:16:12.700
NIH.

00:16:12.700 --> 00:16:13.700
All kinds of things.

00:16:13.700 --> 00:16:14.700
We've underfunded those.

00:16:14.700 --> 00:16:18.360
And finally you need infrastructure.

00:16:18.360 --> 00:16:24.290
Any of you who've come into Kennedy Airport
know that America has been under investing

00:16:24.290 --> 00:16:25.290
in our infrastructure.

00:16:25.290 --> 00:16:30.800
A comparison between US airports and those
in Asia is embarrassing.

00:16:30.800 --> 00:16:35.410
But you need ports and roads if you're gonna
export.

00:16:35.410 --> 00:16:36.520
If you're gonna grow.

00:16:36.520 --> 00:16:37.520
So.

00:16:37.520 --> 00:16:38.830
We've not been investing in these things.

00:16:38.830 --> 00:16:43.860
And one of the reasons we haven't, is when
you have a divided society, those at the top

00:16:43.860 --> 00:16:50.560
worry that if you have too strong of a government,
it might use its powers to redistribute.

00:16:50.560 --> 00:16:55.040
So they'd rather have a weak government that
can't do anything.

00:16:55.040 --> 00:16:56.190
That's tied up.

00:16:56.190 --> 00:16:57.570
That's gridlocked.

00:16:57.570 --> 00:17:02.280
Than a government that might engage in redistribution.

00:17:02.280 --> 00:17:05.259
I'll come back to that in the end.

00:17:05.259 --> 00:17:13.490
But the point of all these are just, some
of the mechanisms by which inequality leads

00:17:13.490 --> 00:17:16.069
to poorer economic performance.

00:17:16.069 --> 00:17:22.879
There's one more final one I want to mention
that's gotten a lot of attention more recently.

00:17:22.879 --> 00:17:28.769
It's not a surprise that the last time inequality
reached the kind of level that it's reached

00:17:28.769 --> 00:17:34.379
more recently in the United States was during
the "roaring '20s."

00:17:34.379 --> 00:17:36.500
Right before the Great Depression.

00:17:36.500 --> 00:17:42.559
And the IMF, the UN Commission, that investigated
the global financial crisis.

00:17:42.559 --> 00:17:49.809
Other scholars have come to the consensus
that inequality is systematically associated

00:17:49.809 --> 00:17:51.250
with instability.

00:17:51.250 --> 00:17:52.649
We have time later in the question period.

00:17:52.649 --> 00:17:55.549
I can try to go through the mechanism by which
that happens.

00:17:55.549 --> 00:17:59.350
But it is a regularity.

00:17:59.350 --> 00:18:10.070
And so one way of thinking about it is, when
you move money, people at the top save a larger

00:18:10.070 --> 00:18:12.600
fraction of their income than people at the
bottom.

00:18:12.600 --> 00:18:16.980
So you move money from the bottom to the top,
there's a lack of demand.

00:18:16.980 --> 00:18:21.481
Or there would be a lack of demand unless
something is done about it.

00:18:21.481 --> 00:18:24.919
And what the Fed did about it was to create
a bubble.

00:18:24.919 --> 00:18:26.429
[chuckles] And it worked.

00:18:26.429 --> 00:18:27.950
For a while.

00:18:27.950 --> 00:18:30.169
But it put our economy in jeopardy.

00:18:30.169 --> 00:18:36.559
And this has happened not only this time,
but it's happened on other occasions.

00:18:36.559 --> 00:18:46.600
So all of these are reasons why greater inequality
is associated with weaker economic performance.

00:18:46.600 --> 00:18:52.700
And that's really one of the main themes of
the book, of "The Price of Inequality."

00:18:52.700 --> 00:18:56.779
We're paying a high price for this inequality.

00:18:56.779 --> 00:19:03.769
This is a markedly different perspective than
that taken by those on the right.

00:19:03.769 --> 00:19:08.470
Those on the right say "We understand you
don't like inequality.

00:19:08.470 --> 00:19:11.960
We wish we could get rid of inequality.

00:19:11.960 --> 00:19:16.370
But we can't without paying a very high price."

00:19:16.370 --> 00:19:19.100
Now old textbooks used to talk about a tradeoff.

00:19:19.100 --> 00:19:25.740
You can get lower inequality but at the cost
of, lower growth, less economic efficiency.

00:19:25.740 --> 00:19:27.179
There's a tradeoff.

00:19:27.179 --> 00:19:34.360
So that what they said in fact was that the
price that you, not only the top would pay,

00:19:34.360 --> 00:19:40.240
but everybody would have to pay if we try
to reduce the degree of inequality is just

00:19:40.240 --> 00:19:41.539
too high.

00:19:41.539 --> 00:19:46.390
What my book argues is quite the contrary.

00:19:46.390 --> 00:19:51.950
That in fact, we are paying a price for not
attacking inequality.

00:19:51.950 --> 00:20:01.039
That we could have, as I say, a stronger economy
and a more equal society.

00:20:01.039 --> 00:20:07.640
One of the concerns I have is that this inequality
then starts to affect not only our economy

00:20:07.640 --> 00:20:10.640
but our democracy, our system of justice.

00:20:10.640 --> 00:20:11.640
Budget battles.

00:20:11.640 --> 00:20:14.249
The conduct of macroeconomic policy.

00:20:14.249 --> 00:20:22.529
I'll try to explain it in a few minutes how
inequality has this kind of pervasive affect

00:20:22.529 --> 00:20:24.820
on our society.

00:20:24.820 --> 00:20:32.380
Before that I wanna discuss a puzzle that
arises in political science.

00:20:32.380 --> 00:20:33.610
In political theory.

00:20:33.610 --> 00:20:36.750
We're supposed to have a democracy.

00:20:36.750 --> 00:20:42.419
And in a democracy with one person, one vote,
the outcome of the democracy is supposed to

00:20:42.419 --> 00:20:44.159
reflect the middle.

00:20:44.159 --> 00:20:47.899
There's a well-developed theory that some
of you may have studied, called "the medium

00:20:47.899 --> 00:20:48.899
voter."

00:20:48.899 --> 00:20:53.610
That the medium voter, half want more spending,
half want less spending.

00:20:53.610 --> 00:20:58.060
And you can go through any issue in the medium
voter theory describes, it's the person in

00:20:58.060 --> 00:21:05.610
the middle that's supposed to be determining
where our polity goes.

00:21:05.610 --> 00:21:12.750
But if you look at the United States, you
look at the decisions we've made in our politics,

00:21:12.750 --> 00:21:16.600
it's very clear that that doesn't describe
what's going on.

00:21:16.600 --> 00:21:22.770
If you look at what's going on, it's better
described by a theory of one dollar, one vote,

00:21:22.770 --> 00:21:25.470
than one person, one vote.

00:21:25.470 --> 00:21:27.309
And the question is, why?

00:21:27.309 --> 00:21:29.049
'cause we have a democracy.

00:21:29.049 --> 00:21:33.370
Why is the outcome so different?

00:21:33.370 --> 00:21:42.530
Well, in discussing the economics and how
the economy leads to the degree of inequality

00:21:42.530 --> 00:21:50.320
that we have, what I point out is that it's
not just market forces.

00:21:50.320 --> 00:21:52.519
Market forces are universal.

00:21:52.519 --> 00:21:54.889
They affect countries all over the world.

00:21:54.889 --> 00:21:59.820
But the way we shape marked forces has resulted
in the US having more inequality than any

00:21:59.820 --> 00:22:01.690
other country.

00:22:01.690 --> 00:22:05.750
So laws and regulation help to shape market
forces.

00:22:05.750 --> 00:22:12.940
An example, for instance, is take a bankruptcy
law.

00:22:12.940 --> 00:22:15.730
Every country has a bankruptcy law but we
are distinct.

00:22:15.730 --> 00:22:21.830
We have two provisions in our bankruptcy law
that is distinctive.

00:22:21.830 --> 00:22:22.830
Are distinctive.

00:22:22.830 --> 00:22:27.770
One of them is at the top, we give priority
to derivatives.

00:22:27.770 --> 00:22:34.249
That says that if a company goes bankrupt,
the derivatives, the CDSs are paid off before

00:22:34.249 --> 00:22:37.380
anybody else, before workers, before anybody
else.

00:22:37.380 --> 00:22:40.850
And we have a law like that, that encourages
derivatives.

00:22:40.850 --> 00:22:41.890
These speculative products.

00:22:41.890 --> 00:22:47.260
Remember that AIG had a 150 billion dollar
bailout?

00:22:47.260 --> 00:22:52.059
That was a result of government encouraging
this through our bankruptcy law.

00:22:52.059 --> 00:22:57.380
At the other end, this may be a sensitive
subject, but in the United States we have

00:22:57.380 --> 00:23:03.269
another distinctive provision of our bankruptcy
law that students cannot discharge their loans

00:23:03.269 --> 00:23:05.750
even in bankruptcy.

00:23:05.750 --> 00:23:10.460
Even if the school does not provide the education
that they promised.

00:23:10.460 --> 00:23:16.389
You know, in other areas of our life, companies
say, "Satisfaction guaranteed or your money

00:23:16.389 --> 00:23:18.340
back."

00:23:18.340 --> 00:23:24.669
These for-profit schools say, "Satisfaction
is almost guaranteed not to occur."

00:23:24.669 --> 00:23:27.190
Because they all, dropout rates are huge.

00:23:27.190 --> 00:23:31.220
But you never get your money back, and in
fact, we're gonna be on your shoulders for

00:23:31.220 --> 00:23:32.220
the rest of your life."

00:23:32.220 --> 00:23:36.350
Well that's the result of politics.

00:23:36.350 --> 00:23:39.429
Of the laws that we passed that shape our
economy.

00:23:39.429 --> 00:23:47.120
That encourage people to provide education
that doesn't really serve the needs.

00:23:47.120 --> 00:23:49.570
Because they can get their money back.

00:23:49.570 --> 00:23:54.029
Well, the same thing is true about politics.

00:23:54.029 --> 00:24:00.270
That the way our political system works is
shaped by the rules and regulations.

00:24:00.270 --> 00:24:06.340
If you have rules and regulations that say,
for instance, affecting lobbying, campaign

00:24:06.340 --> 00:24:11.909
contributions, revolving doors, they determine
the influence of the one percent.

00:24:11.909 --> 00:24:13.750
The people at the top.

00:24:13.750 --> 00:24:18.639
So like, the citizens united, the supreme
court decisions that will allow corporations

00:24:18.639 --> 00:24:27.990
to give unbridled spending gave more influence
to those at the top.

00:24:27.990 --> 00:24:34.100
The consequence of this is that we have a
vicious circle.

00:24:34.100 --> 00:24:39.409
Where economic inequality feeds into inequality
of political power.

00:24:39.409 --> 00:24:44.840
And that inequality of political power leads
to rules and regulations that lead to more

00:24:44.840 --> 00:24:46.399
economic inequality.

00:24:46.399 --> 00:24:54.299
In a what I would call a downward vicious
circle.

00:24:54.299 --> 00:24:59.730
In some ways it's even worse than I've just
described because as ordinary citizens see

00:24:59.730 --> 00:25:03.600
this process in work, they become disillusioned.

00:25:03.600 --> 00:25:09.950
They say "What good is it to vote?"

00:25:09.950 --> 00:25:15.559
And you see the consequence of that in the
last election, 2010.

00:25:15.559 --> 00:25:20.470
Where 80 percent of the young people said
it wasn't worth their while to exercise their

00:25:20.470 --> 00:25:24.929
democratic right to vote.

00:25:24.929 --> 00:25:25.929
That's astounding.

00:25:25.929 --> 00:25:28.240
Other countries are marching to get the right
to vote.

00:25:28.240 --> 00:25:30.690
Countries fighting to get democracy.

00:25:30.690 --> 00:25:35.860
We have democracy but 80 percent of the young
people said it wasn't worth the trouble of

00:25:35.860 --> 00:25:36.889
going to the poll.

00:25:36.889 --> 00:25:40.369
Because no matter who wins, wall street wins.

00:25:40.369 --> 00:25:41.950
The one percent wins.

00:25:41.950 --> 00:25:46.149
And it's not gonna affect what happened.

00:25:46.149 --> 00:25:51.409
But then that itself gives more power to money.

00:25:51.409 --> 00:25:54.889
Because money then has to be used to get out
the vote.

00:25:54.889 --> 00:25:59.419
And they targeted getting out the vote to
those who will support their views.

00:25:59.419 --> 00:26:05.940
So that's one of the reasons why we've wound
up with this kind of distorted democracy that

00:26:05.940 --> 00:26:07.119
we have.

00:26:07.119 --> 00:26:17.160
The other reason that I talk about briefly
is based on some insights from recent research

00:26:17.160 --> 00:26:19.759
and behavioral economics.

00:26:19.759 --> 00:26:22.299
College-age marketing.

00:26:22.299 --> 00:26:27.289
Corporations have discovered that they can
market goods.

00:26:27.289 --> 00:26:30.600
Good example is for instance, the cigarette
companies.

00:26:30.600 --> 00:26:36.629
Were able to persuade most Americans that
there was no credible evidence that cigarettes

00:26:36.629 --> 00:26:37.759
caused cancer.

00:26:37.759 --> 00:26:40.080
Or had other ill-health effects.

00:26:40.080 --> 00:26:44.140
Even though the cigarette companies had in
their files that evidence.

00:26:44.140 --> 00:26:49.679
But they were very effective in casting doubt
about the nature of the scientific evidence.

00:26:49.679 --> 00:26:54.619
And people continued to smoke for several
decades after the evidence was overwhelming.

00:26:54.619 --> 00:27:02.600
Well, if you can sell toxic products you can
also sell toxic ideas.

00:27:02.600 --> 00:27:10.860
And the one percent has both the resources,
the tools, the techniques and the incentive

00:27:10.860 --> 00:27:12.429
to do that.

00:27:12.429 --> 00:27:17.039
And that's again, played a very important
role in shaping our politics.

00:27:17.039 --> 00:27:23.220
And helps explain why we wound up with these
outcomes that seem so out of line with what

00:27:23.220 --> 00:27:28.450
you would expect to get in a democratic society.

00:27:28.450 --> 00:27:35.909
Let me talk just very briefly about three
other, two or three other manifestations of

00:27:35.909 --> 00:27:37.450
this inequality.

00:27:37.450 --> 00:27:41.059
Not only has it put our democracy at peril.

00:27:41.059 --> 00:27:46.610
It's also put our system of justice at peril.

00:27:46.610 --> 00:27:52.460
One of the basic values I think that most
Americans take seriously is justice for all.

00:27:52.460 --> 00:27:57.860
You know, in the Pledge of Allegiance, we
say "Justice for all."

00:27:57.860 --> 00:28:09.779
But in the recent mortgage crisis the mortgage
debacle, what we saw was not justice for all.

00:28:09.779 --> 00:28:17.019
Many Americans were thrown out of their homes
when they didn't owe anything.

00:28:17.019 --> 00:28:24.059
The banks signed an affidavit, said that they'd
looked at the record, and said that this individual

00:28:24.059 --> 00:28:26.239
owed money.

00:28:26.239 --> 00:28:28.000
But they were lying.

00:28:28.000 --> 00:28:29.210
They hadn't looked at the record.

00:28:29.210 --> 00:28:33.919
This was the robo-signing where they just
had so many signed thousands of these a day.

00:28:33.919 --> 00:28:34.950
They hadn't looked at the record.

00:28:34.950 --> 00:28:38.110
And obviously if you haven't looked at the
record you're gonna make a lot of mistakes.

00:28:38.110 --> 00:28:43.200
Now the banks response is that most of the
people that they threw out of their homes

00:28:43.200 --> 00:28:45.999
did owe money.

00:28:45.999 --> 00:28:50.309
That's like a system of justice that says
"most of the people that get capital punishment

00:28:50.309 --> 00:28:51.519
were probably guilty.

00:28:51.519 --> 00:28:55.009
They must have done something wrong."

00:28:55.009 --> 00:28:56.549
But that's not our system of justice.

00:28:56.549 --> 00:28:58.039
"Innocent until proven guilty."

00:28:58.039 --> 00:29:02.309
The burden of proof.

00:29:02.309 --> 00:29:09.739
But the fact of the matter is, after all of
this has been brought to light, not one of

00:29:09.739 --> 00:29:13.600
the people who committed this kind of perjury
to the court, over and over again.

00:29:13.600 --> 00:29:20.140
Not just once, over and over again, has gone
to prison.

00:29:20.140 --> 00:29:24.739
There is some attempt to get financial reparations
to make up for the people who have been thrown

00:29:24.739 --> 00:29:25.911
out of their homes.

00:29:25.911 --> 00:29:30.830
But the result of this if you look and this
is just one example, we've wound up with a

00:29:30.830 --> 00:29:37.500
system that is better described, not "justice
for all" but "justice for those who can afford

00:29:37.500 --> 00:29:38.500
it."

00:29:38.500 --> 00:29:43.840
Now take another issue that's been very big
in the United States in recent years.

00:29:43.840 --> 00:29:47.440
The battle over the budget.

00:29:47.440 --> 00:29:49.929
How do we bring down the deficit?

00:29:49.929 --> 00:29:56.789
And if I begin to analyze that problem, I
begin with a very simple observation.

00:29:56.789 --> 00:30:02.730
Just a little over 10 years ago, 2001, the
US had a large surplus.

00:30:02.730 --> 00:30:09.160
So large that Alan Greenspan said that he
was worried.

00:30:09.160 --> 00:30:13.899
He was worried we were gonna pay back the
entire national debt and that would be very

00:30:13.899 --> 00:30:18.519
hard for him to conduct monetary policy with
no national debt.

00:30:18.519 --> 00:30:22.559
You know the details of how monetary policy
is conducted, is buying and selling national

00:30:22.559 --> 00:30:23.929
debt.

00:30:23.929 --> 00:30:28.919
Now you should understand that this was a
totally specious argument.

00:30:28.919 --> 00:30:32.200
And incredible that anybody took Alan Greenspan
seriously.

00:30:32.200 --> 00:30:35.269
But then he was a hero.

00:30:35.269 --> 00:30:41.659
I cannot believe that if say, in 2015, those
surpluses had persisted and we almost paid

00:30:41.659 --> 00:30:47.840
down the national debt, Alan Greenspan or
a successor could have come to Congress and

00:30:47.840 --> 00:30:51.570
the Administration and say "You know our country
faces a real emergency.

00:30:51.570 --> 00:30:54.519
You need to spend more to create a debt.

00:30:54.519 --> 00:30:57.379
And I know you don't wanna spend.

00:30:57.379 --> 00:31:01.830
But sacrifice, but your country in front of
anybody else.

00:31:01.830 --> 00:31:03.250
Cut taxes, spend more.

00:31:03.250 --> 00:31:05.039
Please, please."

00:31:05.039 --> 00:31:09.749
I can't believe that congress would not have
responded and relatively quickly to this national

00:31:09.749 --> 00:31:10.840
emergency.

00:31:10.840 --> 00:31:11.940
[laughter]

00:31:11.940 --> 00:31:16.559
But somehow Alan Greenspan said "No, we can't
wait until that dire moment, we have to act

00:31:16.559 --> 00:31:20.880
in 2001 to give a tax cut to the richest Americans.

00:31:20.880 --> 00:31:23.129
Let's not look at the details of whether we
can afford it.

00:31:23.129 --> 00:31:27.859
Let's get that tax cut right on the books
as soon as we can."

00:31:27.859 --> 00:31:33.669
What that shows you was that macro-economic
policy, monetary economic policy, these independent

00:31:33.669 --> 00:31:36.940
central bankers really often have a political
agenda.

00:31:36.940 --> 00:31:42.450
They're not these god-like figures who are
only worrying about the details of inflation

00:31:42.450 --> 00:31:45.080
and so forth.

00:31:45.080 --> 00:31:51.989
But more to the point, if you understand that
just over a decade ago we had a surplus and

00:31:51.989 --> 00:31:57.480
you see the large deficits, where would a
reasonable place of beginning to get rid of

00:31:57.480 --> 00:31:58.480
the deficits?

00:31:58.480 --> 00:32:03.590
Well, to ask, how did we go from that surplus
to the deficit and let's see if we should

00:32:03.590 --> 00:32:04.889
reverse those?

00:32:04.889 --> 00:32:08.379
And there are actually only four things.

00:32:08.379 --> 00:32:12.889
This tax cut that we couldn't afford, especially
for the top.

00:32:12.889 --> 00:32:20.440
Two very expensive wars that didn't do anything
and a military buildup beyond that.

00:32:20.440 --> 00:32:23.150
Weapons that don't work against enemies that
don't exist.

00:32:23.150 --> 00:32:24.150
That's the good news.

00:32:24.150 --> 00:32:25.720
That the enemies aren't there.

00:32:25.720 --> 00:32:26.869
The Cold War is over.

00:32:26.869 --> 00:32:30.159
The Defense Department doesn't seem to know
it yet.

00:32:30.159 --> 00:32:38.159
Thirdly, a drug benefit for, I mentioned before
that we don't bargain with the drug companies.

00:32:38.159 --> 00:32:40.970
And that's a half a trillion dollar giveaway
over 10 years.

00:32:40.970 --> 00:32:46.790
And finally, probably one of the most important
is, the recession.

00:32:46.790 --> 00:32:48.289
And this is very important.

00:32:48.289 --> 00:32:54.220
The deficit didn't cause the recession.

00:32:54.220 --> 00:32:56.359
The recession caused the deficit.

00:32:56.359 --> 00:33:02.039
The best way of getting the deficit down would
be put America back to work.

00:33:02.039 --> 00:33:03.039
To create jobs.

00:33:03.039 --> 00:33:06.120
To get America functioning again.

00:33:06.120 --> 00:33:13.269
Well, if you look at the deficit reduction
commissions, a whole set of them.

00:33:13.269 --> 00:33:16.029
What you see is they don't focus on the issues
that I've just described.

00:33:16.029 --> 00:33:17.620
There are all kinds of things.

00:33:17.620 --> 00:33:21.539
Like, can you imagine a deficit reduction
commission that says "Let's lower the corporate

00:33:21.539 --> 00:33:22.869
income tax."

00:33:22.869 --> 00:33:26.200
Now how does that help reduce the deficit?

00:33:26.200 --> 00:33:30.610
Now I agree, you need to reform the tax structure
to get rid of all the loopholes.

00:33:30.610 --> 00:33:32.159
That's important.

00:33:32.159 --> 00:33:34.440
But, lowering the rate?

00:33:34.440 --> 00:33:38.831
What you should be doing is saying "Let's
lower the rate on firms that invest in America

00:33:38.831 --> 00:33:41.470
and raise the rate on firms that don't invest
in America."

00:33:41.470 --> 00:33:47.669
That would provide the incentive for the creation
of more jobs.

00:33:47.669 --> 00:33:55.139
Well, I want to conclude by saying, by discussing
what is it that we can do about this problem?

00:33:55.139 --> 00:34:03.669
In the last chapter I provide an economic
agenda.

00:34:03.669 --> 00:34:07.480
There are many aspects of America's inequality.

00:34:07.480 --> 00:34:09.429
Too much wealth at the top.

00:34:09.429 --> 00:34:10.860
Too many poor people.

00:34:10.860 --> 00:34:12.440
People in poverty have increased.

00:34:12.440 --> 00:34:14.720
A hollowing out of the middle class.

00:34:14.720 --> 00:34:18.610
And each of these requires its own agenda.

00:34:18.610 --> 00:34:19.740
There's no magic bullet.

00:34:19.740 --> 00:34:21.870
There's gonna be lots of things.

00:34:21.870 --> 00:34:25.870
Every law and regulation like the bankruptcy
law, competition law, corporate governance

00:34:25.870 --> 00:34:31.060
laws that allow CEOs to take a larger share
of the pie, of the corporations.

00:34:31.060 --> 00:34:36.900
All of these things help shape the inequality
that we have in our society today.

00:34:36.900 --> 00:34:39.160
And so you can't just do one thing.

00:34:39.160 --> 00:34:40.440
There are many things.

00:34:40.440 --> 00:34:41.640
But it's all doable.

00:34:41.640 --> 00:34:44.160
It's actually not that complicated.

00:34:44.160 --> 00:34:52.690
And other countries have done one or more
of the things that I describe in that agenda.

00:34:52.690 --> 00:34:56.290
The problem of course, is the politics.

00:34:56.290 --> 00:35:00.600
And our political system is distorted so the
question, and it works for the one percent,

00:35:00.600 --> 00:35:04.470
the question is how are we gonna reform the
politics?

00:35:04.470 --> 00:35:10.930
So I end, the question, is there hope?

00:35:10.930 --> 00:35:16.010
And my publisher told me that people don't
buy books if there's no hope.

00:35:16.010 --> 00:35:17.220
[laughter]

00:35:17.220 --> 00:35:20.040
They don't want to finish a book and be depressed.

00:35:20.040 --> 00:35:22.920
It's just not, at least part of the American
personality.

00:35:22.920 --> 00:35:29.700
A few years ago I think I came here and gave
a talk about my book with Linda Bilmes called

00:35:29.700 --> 00:35:31.780
"The Three-Trillion-Dollar War."

00:35:31.780 --> 00:35:36.980
And the book was very influential in shaping
the debate about the war.

00:35:36.980 --> 00:35:41.900
When people started using the, the war, they
said "the three-trillion-dollar war."

00:35:41.900 --> 00:35:47.100
And it helped people understand the huge cost
of the war.

00:35:47.100 --> 00:35:49.370
We were very explicit.

00:35:49.370 --> 00:35:51.900
We had underestimated the cost of the war.

00:35:51.900 --> 00:35:58.520
In particular the numbers that have come in
since then have shown that we were accurate.

00:35:58.520 --> 00:36:03.950
And we were right that we had underestimated
close to one out of two Americans coming back

00:36:03.950 --> 00:36:07.080
from Afghanistan and Iraq are disabled.

